I don&#39;t think there is a function in the core libraries that will compose these comparators for you. But it is a simple function:

```java
private static &lt;T&gt; Comparator&lt;T&gt; compose(
    Comparator&lt;? super T&gt; before, 
    Comparator&lt;T&gt; after) {

  return (o1, o2) -&gt; {
    int diff = before.compare(o1, o2);
    return diff == 0 ? after.compare(o1, o2) : diff;
  };
}
```

Then you can use it as

```java
private static final Comparator&lt;ChildA&gt; combined = 
    compose(commonComparator, childAComparator);
```

Note that because [`thenComparing()`][1] has bounds of `? super T`, it can only compose the two comparators when the child comparator is applied first, but in this case, the parent comparator must be applied first.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Comparator.html#thenComparing(java.util.Comparator)

